# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: cat-language
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:cat-language/combinatory-logic] Combinatory logic was originally intended as a 'pre-logic' that would clarify the role of quantified variables in logic, essentially by eliminating them.
[src:cat-language/combinatory-logic] Another way of eliminating quantified variables is Quine's predicate functor logic.
[src:cat-language/combinatory-logic] While the expressive power of combinatory logic typically exceeds that of first-order logic, the expressive power of predicate functor logic is identical to that of first-order logic (Quine 1960, 1966, 1976).
[src:cat-language/combinatory-logic] The inventor of combinatory logic, Moses Schönfinkel, published nothing on combinatory logic after his original 1924 paper.
[src:cat-language/combinatory-logic] Haskell Curry rediscovered the combinators while working as an instructor at Princeton University in late 1927.
[src:cat-language/combinatory-logic] In the late 1930s, Alonzo Church and his students at Princeton invented a rival formalism for functional abstraction, the lambda calculus, which proved more popular than combinatory logic.
[src:cat-language/combinatory-logic] The upshot of these historical contingencies was that until theoretical computer science began taking an interest in combinatory logic in the 1960s and 1970s, nearly all work on the subject was by Haskell Curry and his students, or by Robert Feys in Belgium.
[src:cat-language/combinatory-logic] Curry and Feys (1958), and Curry *et al.* (1972) survey the early history of combinatory logic.
[src:cat-language/combinatory-logic] For a more modern treatment of combinatory logic and the lambda calculus together, see the book by Barendregt, which reviews the models Dana Scott devised for combinatory logic in the 1960s and 1970s.
[src:cat-language/combinatory-logic] In computer science, combinatory logic is used as a simplified model of computation, used in computability theory and proof theory.
[src:cat-language/combinatory-logic] Despite its simplicity, combinatory logic captures many essential features of computation.
[src:cat-language/combinatory-logic] Combinatory logic can be viewed as a variant of the lambda calculus, in which lambda expressions (representing functional abstraction) are replaced by a limited set of *combinators*, primitive functions without free variables.
[src:cat-language/combinatory-logic] It is easy to transform lambda expressions into combinator expressions, and combinator reduction is much simpler than lambda reduction.
[src:cat-language/combinatory-logic] Hence combinatory logic has been used to model some non-strict functional programming languages and hardware.
[src:cat-language/combinatory-logic] The purest form of this view is the programming language Unlambda, whose sole primitives are the S and K combinators augmented with character input/output.
[src:cat-language/combinatory-logic] Although not a practical programming language, Unlambda is of some theoretical interest.
[src:cat-language/combinatory-logic] Combinatory logic can be given a variety of interpretations.
[src:cat-language/combinatory-logic] Many early papers by Curry showed how to translate axiom sets for conventional logic into combinatory logic equations.
[src:cat-language/combinatory-logic] Dana Scott in the 1960s and 1970s showed how to marry model theory and combinatory logic.
[src:cat-language/combinatory-logic] where v is a variable name drawn from a predefined infinite set of variable names, and $E_{1}$ and $E_{2}$ are lambda-terms.
[src:cat-language/combinatory-logic] Terms of the form $\lambda v.E_{1}$ are called *abstractions*.
[src:cat-language/combinatory-logic] The variable v is called the formal parameter of the abstraction, and $E_{1}$ is the *body* of the abstraction.
[src:cat-language/combinatory-logic] The term $\lambda v.E_{1}$ represents the function which, applied to an argument, binds the formal parameter v to the argument and then computes the resulting value of $E_{1}$ — that is, it returns $E_{1}$ , with every occurrence of v replaced by the argument.
[src:cat-language/combinatory-logic] Terms of the form $E_{1}E_{2}$ are called *applications*.
[src:cat-language/combinatory-logic] Applications model function invocation or execution: the function represented by $E_{1}$ is to be invoked, with $E_{2}$ as its argument, and the result is computed.
[src:cat-language/combinatory-logic] If $E_{1}$ (sometimes called the *applicand*) is an abstraction, the term may be *reduced*: $E_{2}$ , the argument, may be substituted into the body of $E_{1}$ in place of the formal parameter of $E_{1}$ , and the result is a new lambda term which is *equivalent* to the old one.
[src:cat-language/combinatory-logic] If a lambda term contains no subterms of the form $((\lambda v.E_{1})E_{2})$ then it cannot be reduced, and is said to be in normal form.
[src:cat-language/combinatory-logic] The expression $E[v:=a]$ represents the result of taking the term E and replacing all free occurrences of v in it with a .
[src:cat-language/combinatory-logic] By convention, we take $(abc)$ as shorthand for $((ab)c)$ (i.e., application is left associative).
[src:cat-language/combinatory-logic] The motivation for this definition of reduction is that it captures the essential behavior of all mathematical functions.
[src:cat-language/combinatory-logic] For example, consider the function that computes the square of a number.
[src:cat-language/combinatory-logic] (Using " * " to indicate multiplication.) x here is the formal parameter of the function.
[src:cat-language/combinatory-logic] To evaluate the resulting expression $3*3$ , we would have to resort to our knowledge of multiplication and the number 3.
[src:cat-language/combinatory-logic] Since any computation is simply a composition of the evaluation of suitable functions on suitable primitive arguments, this simple substitution principle suffices to capture the essential mechanism of computation.
[src:cat-language/combinatory-logic] Moreover, in lambda calculus, notions such as '3' and ' * ' can be represented without any need for externally defined primitive operators or constants.
[src:cat-language/combinatory-logic] It is possible to identify terms in lambda calculus, which, when suitably interpreted, behave like the number 3 and like the multiplication operator, q.v.
[src:cat-language/combinatory-logic] Lambda calculus is known to be computationally equivalent in power to many other plausible models for computation (including Turing machines); that is, any calculation that can be accomplished in any of these other models can be expressed in lambda calculus, and vice versa.
[src:cat-language/combinatory-logic] According to the Church–Turing thesis, both models can express any possible computation.
[src:cat-language/combinatory-logic] It is perhaps surprising that lambda-calculus can represent any conceivable computation using only the simple notions of function abstraction and application based on simple textual substitution of terms for variables.
[src:cat-language/combinatory-logic] But even more remarkable is that abstraction is not even required.
[src:cat-language/combinatory-logic] *Combinatory logic* is a model of computation equivalent to lambda calculus, but without abstraction.
[src:cat-language/combinatory-logic] The advantage of this is that evaluating expressions in lambda calculus is quite complicated because the semantics of substitution must be specified with great care to avoid variable capture problems.
[src:cat-language/combinatory-logic] In contrast, evaluating expressions in combinatory logic is much simpler, because there is no notion of substitution.
[src:cat-language/combinatory-logic] Since abstraction is the only way to manufacture functions in the lambda calculus, something must replace it in the combinatory calculus.
[src:cat-language/combinatory-logic] Instead of abstraction, combinatory calculus provides a limited set of primitive functions out of which other functions may be built.
[src:cat-language/combinatory-logic] The primitive functions are *combinators*, or functions that, when seen as lambda terms, contain no free variables.
[src:cat-language/combinatory-logic] This is the same general convention (left-associativity) as for multiple application in lambda calculus.
[src:cat-language/combinatory-logic] where E is a term mentioning only variables from the set $\{x_{1}\dots x_{n}\}$ .
[src:cat-language/combinatory-logic] It is in this way that primitive combinators behave as functions.
[src:cat-language/combinatory-logic] S applies x to y after first substituting z into each of them.
[src:cat-language/combinatory-logic] Or put another way, x is applied to y inside the environment z .
[src:cat-language/combinatory-logic] Note that although $((S\,K\,K)\,x)=(Ix)$ for any x , $(S\,K\,K)$ itself is not equal to I .
[src:cat-language/combinatory-logic] We say the terms are extensionally equal.
[src:cat-language/combinatory-logic] Extensional equality captures the mathematical notion of the equality of functions: that two functions are considered *equal* if they always produce the same results for the same arguments.
[src:cat-language/combinatory-logic] In contrast, the terms themselves, together with the reduction of primitive combinators, capture the notion of *intensional equality* of functions: that two functions are considered *equal* only if they have identical implementations up to the expansion of primitive combinators.
[src:cat-language/combinatory-logic] There are many ways to implement an identity function; $(S\,K\,K)$ and I are among these ways. $(S\,K\,S)$ is yet another.
[src:cat-language/combinatory-logic] We will use the word *equivalent* to mean extensional equality.
[src:cat-language/combinatory-logic] A more interesting combinator is the fixed point combinator or Y combinator, which can be used to implement recursion.
[src:cat-language/combinatory-logic] Note that *T*[ ] as given is not a well-typed mathematical function, but rather a term rewriter: Although it eventually yields a combinator, the transformation may generate intermediary expressions that are neither lambda terms nor combinators, via rule (5).
[src:cat-language/combinatory-logic] This process is also known as *abstraction elimination*.
[src:cat-language/combinatory-logic] This definition is exhaustive: any lambda expression will be subject to exactly one of these rules (see Summary of lambda calculus above).
[src:cat-language/combinatory-logic] It is related to the process of *bracket abstraction*, which takes an expression *E* built from variables and application and produces a combinator expression [x]E in which the variable x is not free, such that [*x*]*E x* = *E* holds.
[src:cat-language/combinatory-logic] Bracket abstraction induces a translation from lambda terms to combinator expressions, by interpreting lambda-abstractions using the bracket abstraction algorithm.
[src:cat-language/combinatory-logic] In general, the *T*[ ] construction may expand a lambda term of length *n* to a combinatorial term of length Θ(*n*3).
[src:cat-language/combinatory-logic] The *T*[ ] transformation is motivated by a desire to eliminate abstraction.
[src:cat-language/combinatory-logic] Two special cases, rules 3 and 4, are trivial: *λx*.*x* is clearly equivalent to **I**, and *λx*.*E* is clearly equivalent to (**K** *T*[*E*]) if *x* does not appear free in *E*.
[src:cat-language/combinatory-logic] The first two rules are also simple: Variables convert to themselves, and applications, which are allowed in combinatory terms, are converted to combinators simply by converting the applicand and the argument to combinators.
[src:cat-language/combinatory-logic] It is rules 5 and 6 that are of interest.
[src:cat-language/combinatory-logic] Rule 5 simply says that to convert a complex abstraction to a combinator, we must first convert its body to a combinator, and then eliminate the abstraction.
[src:cat-language/combinatory-logic] Rule 6 actually eliminates the abstraction.
[src:cat-language/combinatory-logic] *E*1 and *E*2 each contain strictly fewer applications than (*E*1 *E*2), so the recursion must terminate in a lambda term with no applications at all—either a variable, or a term of the form *λx*.*E*.
[src:cat-language/combinatory-logic] With the η-reduction rule, *λf*.*λx*.(*f* *x*) is transformed into **I**.
[src:cat-language/combinatory-logic] There are one-point bases from which every combinator can be composed extensionally equal to *any* lambda term.
[src:cat-language/combinatory-logic] Since {**K**, **S**} is a basis, it follows that {**X**} is a basis too.
[src:cat-language/combinatory-logic] The Iota programming language uses **X** as its sole combinator.
[src:cat-language/combinatory-logic] In fact, there exist infinitely many such bases.
[src:cat-language/combinatory-logic] These combinators are extremely useful when translating predicate logic or lambda calculus into combinator expressions.
[src:cat-language/combinatory-logic] They were also used by Curry, and much later by David Turner, whose name has been associated with their computational use.
[src:cat-language/combinatory-logic] The motivation here is that **B** and **C** are limited versions of **S**.
[src:cat-language/combinatory-logic] Whereas **S** takes a value and substitutes it into both the applicand and its argument before performing the application, **C** performs the substitution only in the applicand, and **B** only in the argument.
[src:cat-language/combinatory-logic] The modern names for the combinators come from Haskell Curry's doctoral thesis of 1930 (see B, C, K, W System).
[src:cat-language/combinatory-logic] The reduction in combinator size that results from the new transformation rules can also be achieved without introducing **B** and **C**, as demonstrated in Section 3.2 of Tromp (2008).
[src:cat-language/combinatory-logic] A distinction must be made between the **CL**K as described in this article and the **CL**I calculus.
[src:cat-language/combinatory-logic] The distinction corresponds to that between the λK and the λI calculus.
[src:cat-language/combinatory-logic] As a consequence, combinator **K** is not present in the λI calculus nor in the **CL**I calculus.
[src:cat-language/combinatory-logic] The constants of **CL**I are: **I**, **B**, **C** and **S**, which form a basis from which all **CL**I terms can be composed (modulo equality).
[src:cat-language/combinatory-logic] Every λI term can be converted into an extensionally equal **CL**I combinator according to rules similar to those presented above for the conversion of λK terms into **CL**K combinators.
[src:cat-language/combinatory-logic] Note, however, that this transformation is not the inverse transformation of any of the versions of *T*[ ] that we have seen.
[src:cat-language/combinatory-logic] A normal form is any combinatory term in which the primitive combinators that occur, if any, are not applied to enough arguments to be simplified.
[src:cat-language/combinatory-logic] It is undecidable whether a general combinatory term has a normal form; whether two combinatory terms are equivalent, etc.
[src:cat-language/combinatory-logic] This can be shown in a similar way as for the corresponding problems for lambda terms.
[src:cat-language/combinatory-logic] The undecidable problems above (equivalence, existence of normal form, etc.) take as input syntactic representations of terms under a suitable encoding (e.g., Church encoding).
[src:cat-language/combinatory-logic] One may also consider a toy trivial computation model where we "compute" properties of terms by means of combinators applied directly to the terms themselves as arguments, rather than to their syntactic representations.
[src:cat-language/combinatory-logic] A predicate **N** is *nontrivial* if there are two arguments *A* and *B* such that **N** *A* = **T** and **N** *B* = **F**.
[src:cat-language/combinatory-logic] A combinator **N** is *complete* if **N***M* has a normal form for every argument *M*.
[src:cat-language/combinatory-logic] An analogue of Rice's theorem for this toy model then says that every complete predicate is trivial.
[src:cat-language/combinatory-logic] The proof of this theorem is rather simple.
[src:cat-language/combinatory-logic] Suppose there is a complete non trivial predicate, say **N**.
[src:cat-language/combinatory-logic] Hence (**N** ABSURDUM) is neither **T** nor **F**, which contradicts the presupposition that **N** would be a complete non trivial predicate.
[src:cat-language/combinatory-logic] From this undefinability theorem it immediately follows that there is no complete predicate that can discriminate between terms that have a normal form and terms that do not have a normal form.
[src:cat-language/combinatory-logic] If EQUAL would exist, then for all *A*, *λx.*(EQUAL *x A*) would have to be a complete non trivial predicate.
[src:cat-language/combinatory-logic] This shows that definability by predicates is a not a reasonable model of decidability.
[src:cat-language/combinatory-logic] David Turner used his combinators to implement the SASL programming language.
[src:cat-language/combinatory-logic] Iverson used primitives based on Curry's combinators in his J programming language, a successor to APL.
[src:cat-language/combinatory-logic] This enabled what Iverson called tacit programming, that is, programming in functional expressions containing no variables, along with powerful tools for working with such programs.
[src:cat-language/combinatory-logic] It turns out that tacit programming is possible in any APL-like language with user-defined operators.
[src:cat-language/combinatory-logic] The Curry–Howard isomorphism implies a connection between logic and programming: every proof of a theorem of intuitionistic logic corresponds to a reduction of a typed lambda term, and conversely.
[src:cat-language/combinatory-logic] Moreover, theorems can be identified with function type signatures.
[src:cat-language/combinatory-logic] Specifically, a typed combinatory logic corresponds to a Hilbert system in proof theory.
[src:cat-language/combinatory-logic] The calculus consisting of **AK**, **AS**, and **MP** is complete for the implicational fragment of the intuitionistic logic, which can be seen as follows.
[src:cat-language/combinatory-logic] Consider the set *W* of all deductively closed sets of formulas, ordered by inclusion.
[src:cat-language/combinatory-logic] This definition obeys the conditions on satisfaction of →: on one hand, if $X\Vdash A\to B$ , and $Y\in W$ is such that $Y\supseteq X$ and $Y\Vdash A$ , then $Y\Vdash B$ by modus ponens.
[src:cat-language/combinatory-logic] On the other hand, if $X\not \Vdash A\to B$ , then $X,A\not \vdash B$ by the deduction theorem, thus the deductive closure of $X\cup \{A\}$ is an element $Y\in W$ such that $Y\supseteq X$ , $Y\Vdash A$ , and $Y\not \Vdash B$ .
[src:cat-language/combinatory-logic] Let *A* be any formula which is not provable in the calculus.
[src:cat-language/combinatory-logic] Then *A* does not belong to the deductive closure *X* of the empty set, thus $X\not \Vdash A$ , and *A* is not intuitionistically valid.
[src:cat-language/concatenative-programming-language] A **concatenative programming language** is a point-free computer programming language in which all expressions denote functions, and the juxtaposition of expressions denotes function composition.
[src:cat-language/concatenative-programming-language] Concatenative programming replaces function application, which is common in other programming paradigms, with function composition as the default way to build subroutines.
[src:cat-language/concatenative-programming-language] Functions and procedures written in concatenative style are not value level, i.e., they typically do not represent the data structures they operate on with explicit names or identifiers.
[src:cat-language/concatenative-programming-language] Instead they are function level – a function is defined as a pipeline, or a sequence of operations that take parameters from an implicit data structure on which all functions operate, and return the function results to that shared structure so that it will be used by the next operator.
[src:cat-language/concatenative-programming-language] The combination of compositional semantics with a syntax that mirrors such a semantic makes concatenative languages highly amenable to algebraic manipulation of programs; although it may be difficult to write mathematical expressions directly in them.
[src:cat-language/concatenative-programming-language] Concatenative languages can be implemented efficiently with a stack machine, and are commonly present implicitly in virtual machines in the form of their instruction sets.
[src:cat-language/concatenative-programming-language] The first concatenative programming language was Forth, although Joy was the first language which was termed concatenative.
[src:cat-language/concatenative-programming-language] Other concatenative languages are dc, Factor, Onyx, PostScript, RPL, Staapl, and experimental and discontinued ones including: Enchilada, Om, XY.
[src:cat-language/concatenative-programming-language] Most existing concatenative languages are stack-based.
[src:cat-language/concatenative-programming-language] This is not required, and other models have been proposed.
[src:cat-language/concatenative-programming-language] Concatenative languages are currently used for embedded, desktop, and web programming, as target languages, and for research purposes.
[src:cat-language/concatenative-programming-language] Most concatenative languages are dynamically typed.
[src:cat-language/concatenative-programming-language] Exceptions include the statically typed Cat language and its successor, Kitten.
[src:cat-language/homoiconicity] In computer programming, **homoiconicity** (from the Greek words *homo-* meaning "the same" and *icon* meaning "representation") is an informal property of some programming languages.
[src:cat-language/homoiconicity] A language is **homoiconic** if a program written in it can be manipulated as data using the language.
[src:cat-language/homoiconicity] The program's internal representation can thus be inferred just by reading the program itself.
[src:cat-language/homoiconicity] This property is often summarized by saying that the language treats code as data.
[src:cat-language/homoiconicity] The informality of the property arises from the fact that, strictly, this applies to almost all programming languages.
[src:cat-language/homoiconicity] No consensus exists on a precise definition of the property.
[src:cat-language/homoiconicity] In a homoiconic language, the primary representation of programs is also a data structure in a primitive type of the language itself.
[src:cat-language/homoiconicity] This makes metaprogramming easier than in a language without this property: reflection in the language (examining the program's entities at runtime) depends on a single, homogeneous structure, and it does not have to handle several different structures that would appear in a complex syntax.
[src:cat-language/homoiconicity] Homoiconic languages typically include full support of syntactic macros, allowing the programmer to express transformations of programs in a concise way.
[src:cat-language/homoiconicity] A commonly cited example is Lisp, which was created to allow for easy list manipulations and where the structure is given by S-expressions that take the form of nested lists, and can be manipulated by other Lisp code.
[src:cat-language/homoiconicity] Other examples are the programming languages Clojure (a contemporary dialect of Lisp), Rebol (also its successor Red), Refal, Prolog, XSLT, and possibly Julia (see the section “Implementation methods” for more details).
[src:cat-language/homoiconicity] The researchers implicated in this quote might be neurophysiologist and cybernetician Warren Sturgis McCulloch (note the difference in the surname from the note) and philosopher, logician and mathematician Charles Sanders Peirce.
[src:cat-language/homoiconicity] Pierce indeed used the term "icon" in his Semiotic Theory.
[src:cat-language/homoiconicity] According to Peirce, there are three kinds of sign in communication: the icon, the index and the symbol.
[src:cat-language/homoiconicity] The icon is the simplest representation: an icon physically resembles that which it denotes.
[src:cat-language/homoiconicity] One advantage of homoiconicity is that extending the language with new concepts typically becomes simpler, as data representing code can be passed between the meta and base layer of the program.
[src:cat-language/homoiconicity] The abstract syntax tree of a function may be composed and manipulated as a data structure in the meta layer, and then evaluated.
[src:cat-language/homoiconicity] It can be much easier to understand how to manipulate the code since it can be more easily understood as simple data (since the format of the language itself is as a data format).
[src:cat-language/homoiconicity] A typical demonstration of homoiconicity is the meta-circular evaluator.
[src:cat-language/homoiconicity] All Von Neumann architecture systems, which includes the vast majority of general purpose computers today, can implicitly be described as homoiconic due to the way that raw machine code executes in memory, the data type being bytes in memory.
[src:cat-language/homoiconicity] However, this feature can also be abstracted to the programming language level.
[src:cat-language/homoiconicity] Languages such as Lisp and its dialects, such as Scheme, Clojure, and Racket employ S-expressions to achieve homoiconicity, and are considered the "Purest" forms of homoiconicity, as these languages use the same representation for both data and code.
[src:cat-language/homoiconicity] Other languages provide data structures for easily and efficiently manipulating code.
[src:cat-language/homoiconicity] Notable examples of this weaker form of homoiconicity include Julia, Nim, and Elixir.
[src:cat-language/homoiconicity] Lisp uses S-expressions as an external representation for data and code.
[src:cat-language/homoiconicity] S-expressions can be read with the primitive Lisp function `READ`.
[src:cat-language/homoiconicity] `READ` returns Lisp data: lists, symbols, numbers, strings.
[src:cat-language/homoiconicity] The primitive Lisp function `EVAL` uses Lisp code represented as Lisp data, computes side-effects and returns a result.
[src:cat-language/homoiconicity] The result will be printed by the primitive function `PRINT`, which creates an external S-expression from Lisp data.
[src:cat-language/homoiconicity] Lisp data, a list using different data types: (sub)lists, symbols, strings and integer numbers.
[src:cat-language/homoiconicity] The example uses lists, symbols and numbers.
[src:cat-language/homoiconicity] The operator `:-` separates the head and the body of a clause.
[src:cat-language/homoiconicity] With `assert/1`* we add it to the existing clauses (add it to the "database"), so we can call it later.
[src:cat-language/homoiconicity] In other languages we would call it "creating a function during runtime".
[src:cat-language/homoiconicity] We can also remove clauses from the database with `abolish/1`, or `retract/1`.
[src:cat-language/homoiconicity] `call` is analogous to Lisp's `eval` function.
[src:cat-language/homoiconicity] The concept of treating code as data and the manipulation and evaluation thereof can be demonstrated very neatly in Rebol.
[src:cat-language/homoiconicity] (Rebol, unlike Lisp, does not require parentheses to separate expressions).
[src:cat-language/homoiconicity] (`repeat` is in fact a built-in function in Rebol and is not a language construct or keyword).
[src:cat-language/homoiconicity] The block can still be interpreted by using the `do` function provided in Rebol (similar to `eval` in Lisp).
[src:cat-language/stack-machine] In computer science, computer engineering and programming language implementations, a **stack machine** is a computer processor or a process virtual machine in which the primary interaction is moving short-lived temporary values to and from a push-down stack.
[src:cat-language/stack-machine] In the case of a hardware processor, a hardware stack is used.
[src:cat-language/stack-machine] The use of a stack significantly reduces the required number of processor registers.
[src:cat-language/stack-machine] Stack machines extend push-down automata with additional load/store operations or multiple stacks and hence are Turing-complete.
[src:cat-language/stack-machine] Most or all stack machine instructions assume that operands will be from the stack, and results placed in the stack.
[src:cat-language/stack-machine] The stack easily holds more than two inputs or more than one result, so a rich set of operations can be computed.
[src:cat-language/stack-machine] In stack machine code (sometimes called p-code), instructions will frequently have only an opcode commanding an operation, with no additional fields identifying a constant, register or memory cell, known as a **zero address format**.
[src:cat-language/stack-machine] A computer that operates in such a way that the majority of its instructions do not include explicit addresses is said to utilize zero-address instructions.
[src:cat-language/stack-machine] This greatly simplifies instruction decoding.
[src:cat-language/stack-machine] Branches, load immediates, and load/store instructions require an argument field, but stack machines often arrange that the frequent cases of these still fit together with the opcode into a compact group of bits.
[src:cat-language/stack-machine] The selection of operands from prior results is done implicitly by ordering the instructions.
[src:cat-language/stack-machine] Some stack machine instruction sets are intended for interpretive execution of a virtual machine, rather than driving hardware directly.
[src:cat-language/stack-machine] Integer constant operands are pushed by `Push` or `Load Immediate` instructions.
[src:cat-language/stack-machine] Memory is often accessed by separate `Load` or `Store` instructions containing a memory address or calculating the address from values in the stack.
[src:cat-language/stack-machine] All practical stack machines have variants of the load–store opcodes for accessing local variables and formal parameters without explicit address calculations.
[src:cat-language/stack-machine] This can be by offsets from the current top-of-stack address, or by offsets from a stable frame-base register.
[src:cat-language/stack-machine] The instruction set carries out most ALU actions with postfix (reverse Polish notation) operations that work only on the expression stack, not on data registers or main memory cells.
[src:cat-language/stack-machine] This can be very convenient for executing high-level languages because most arithmetic expressions can be easily translated into postfix notation.
[src:cat-language/stack-machine] For example, consider the expression *A**(*B*−*C*)+(*D*+*E*), written in reverse Polish notation as *A* *B* *C* − * *D* *E* + +.
[src:cat-language/stack-machine] The arithmetic operations "subtract", "multiply", and "add" act on the two topmost operands of the stack.
[src:cat-language/stack-machine] The computer takes both operands from the topmost (most recent) values of the stack.
[src:cat-language/stack-machine] The computer replaces those two values with the calculated difference, sum, or product.
[src:cat-language/stack-machine] In other words the instruction's operands are "popped" off the stack, and its result(s) are then "pushed" back onto the stack, ready for the next instruction.
[src:cat-language/stack-machine] Stack machines may have their expression stack and their call-return stack separated or as one integrated structure.
[src:cat-language/stack-machine] If they are separated, the instructions of the stack machine can be pipelined with fewer interactions and less design complexity, so it will usually run faster.
[src:cat-language/stack-machine] Optimisation of compiled stack code is quite possible.
[src:cat-language/stack-machine] Back-end optimisation of compiler output has been demonstrated to significantly improve code, and potentially performance, whilst global optimisation within the compiler itself achieves further gains.
[src:cat-language/stack-machine] Some stack machines have a stack of limited size, implemented as a register file.
[src:cat-language/stack-machine] A large register file uses a lot of transistors and hence this method is only suitable for small systems.
[src:cat-language/stack-machine] A few machines have both an expression stack in memory and a separate register stack.
[src:cat-language/stack-machine] In this case, software, or an interrupt may move data between them.
[src:cat-language/stack-machine] Some machines have a stack of unlimited size, implemented as an array in RAM, which is cached by some number of "top of stack" address registers to reduce memory access.
[src:cat-language/stack-machine] Except for explicit "load from memory" instructions, the order of operand usage is identical with the order of the operands in the data stack, so excellent prefetching can be accomplished easily.
[src:cat-language/stack-machine] It compiles to `Load X`; `Load 1`; `Add`.
[src:cat-language/stack-machine] The next step up from this is a stack machine or interpreter with a single top-of-stack register.
[src:cat-language/stack-machine] for a total of 3 data cache references, worst-case.
[src:cat-language/stack-machine] Generally, interpreters don't track emptiness, because they don't have to—anything below the stack pointer is a non-empty value, and the TOS cache register is always kept hot.
[src:cat-language/stack-machine] Typical Java interpreters do not buffer the top-of-stack this way, however, because the program and stack have a mix of short and wide data values.
[src:cat-language/stack-machine] If the hardwired stack machine has 2 or more top-stack registers, or a register file, then all memory access is avoided in this example and there is only 1 data cache cycle.
[src:cat-language/stack-machine] Description of such a method requiring only two values at a time to be held in registers, with a limited set of pre-defined operands that were able to be extended by definition of further operands, functions and subroutines, was first provided at conference by Robert S.
[src:cat-language/stack-machine] Pure stack machines are quite inefficient for procedures which access multiple fields from the same object.
[src:cat-language/stack-machine] The stack machine code must reload the object pointer for each pointer+offset calculation.
[src:cat-language/stack-machine] A common fix for this is to add some register-machine features to the stack machine: a visible register file dedicated to holding addresses, and register-style instructions for doing loads and simple address calculations.
[src:cat-language/stack-machine] It is uncommon to have the registers be fully general purpose, because then there is no strong reason to have an expression stack and postfix instructions.
[src:cat-language/stack-machine] Another common hybrid is to start with a register machine architecture, and add another memory address mode which emulates the push or pop operations of stack machines: "memaddress = reg; reg += instr.displ".
[src:cat-language/stack-machine] This was first used in DEC's PDP-11 minicomputer.
[src:cat-language/stack-machine] This feature was carried forward in VAX computers and in Motorola 6809 and 68000 series microprocessors.
[src:cat-language/stack-machine] This allowed the use of simpler stack methods in early compilers.
[src:cat-language/stack-machine] It also efficiently supported virtual machines using stack interpreters or threaded code.
[src:cat-language/stack-machine] However, this feature did not help the register machine's own code to become as compact as pure stack machine code.
[src:cat-language/stack-machine] Also, the execution speed was less than when compiling well to the register architecture.
[src:cat-language/stack-machine] It is faster to change the top-of-stack pointer only occasionally (once per call or return) rather than constantly stepping it up and down throughout each program statement, and it is even faster to avoid memory references entirely.
[src:cat-language/stack-machine] More recently, so-called second-generation stack machines have adopted a dedicated collection of registers to serve as address registers, off-loading the task of memory addressing from the data stack.
[src:cat-language/stack-machine] For example, MuP21 relies on a register called "A", while the more recent GreenArrays processors relies on two registers: A and B.
[src:cat-language/stack-machine] The Intel x86 family of microprocessors have a register-style (accumulator) instruction set for most operations, but use stack instructions for its x87, Intel 8087 floating point arithmetic, dating back to the iAPX87 (8087) coprocessor for the 8086 and 8088.
[src:cat-language/stack-machine] That is, there are no programmer-accessible floating point registers, but only an 80-bit wide, 8-level deep stack.
[src:cat-language/stack-machine] The x87 relies heavily on the x86 CPU for assistance in performing its operations.
[src:cat-language/stack-machine] Most current computers (of any instruction set style) and most compilers use a large call-return stack in memory to organize the short-lived local variables and return links for all currently active procedures or functions.
[src:cat-language/stack-machine] Each nested call creates a new **stack frame** in memory, which persists until that call completes.
[src:cat-language/stack-machine] This call-return stack may be entirely managed by the hardware via specialized address registers and special address modes in the instructions.
[src:cat-language/stack-machine] Or it may be merely a set of conventions followed by the compilers, using generic registers and register+offset address modes.
[src:cat-language/stack-machine] Since this technique is now nearly universal, even on register machines, it is not helpful to refer to all these machines as stack machines.
[src:cat-language/stack-machine] That term is commonly reserved for machines which also use an expression stack and stack-only arithmetic instructions to evaluate the pieces of a single statement.
[src:cat-language/stack-machine] Computers commonly provide direct, efficient access to the program's global variables and to the local variables of only the current innermost procedure or function, the topmost stack frame.
[src:cat-language/stack-machine] "Up level" addressing of the contents of callers' stack frames is usually not needed and not supported as directly by the hardware.
[src:cat-language/stack-machine] If needed, compilers support this by passing in frame pointers as additional, hidden parameters.
[src:cat-language/stack-machine] Some Burroughs stack machines do support up-level refs directly in the hardware, with specialized address modes and a special "display" register file holding the frame addresses of all outer scopes.
[src:cat-language/stack-machine] Currently, only MCST Elbrus has done this in hardware.
[src:cat-language/stack-machine] When Niklaus Wirth developed the first Pascal compiler for the CDC 6000 series, he found that it was faster overall to pass in the frame pointers as a chain, rather than constantly updating complete arrays of frame pointers.
[src:cat-language/stack-machine] This software method also adds no overhead for common languages like C which lack up-level refs.
[src:cat-language/stack-machine] The same Burroughs machines also supported nesting of tasks or threads.
[src:cat-language/stack-machine] The task and its creator share the stack frames that existed at the time of task creation, but not the creator's subsequent frames nor the task's own frames.
[src:cat-language/stack-machine] This was supported by a cactus stack, whose layout diagram resembled the trunk and arms of a Saguaro cactus.
[src:cat-language/stack-machine] Each task had its own memory segment holding its stack and the frames that it owns.
[src:cat-language/stack-machine] The base of this stack is linked to the middle of its creator's stack.
[src:cat-language/stack-machine] In machines with a conventional flat address space, the creator stack and task stacks would be separate heap objects in one heap.
[src:cat-language/stack-machine] In some programming languages, the outer-scope data environments are not always nested in time.
[src:cat-language/stack-machine] These languages organize their procedure "activation records" as separate heap objects rather than as stack frames appended to a linear stack.
[src:cat-language/stack-machine] In simple languages like Forth that lack local variables and naming of parameters, stack frames would contain nothing more than return branch addresses and frame management overhead.
[src:cat-language/stack-machine] So their return stack holds bare return addresses rather than frames.
[src:cat-language/stack-machine] The return stack is separate from the data value stack, to improve the flow of call setup and returns.
[src:cat-language/stack-machine] Stack machines are often compared to register machines, which hold values in an array of registers.
[src:cat-language/stack-machine] Register machines may store stack-like structures in this array, but a register machine has instructions which circumvent the stack interface.
[src:cat-language/stack-machine] Register machines routinely outperform stack machines, and stack machines have remained a niche player in hardware systems.
[src:cat-language/stack-machine] But stack machines are often used in implementing virtual machines because of their simplicity and ease of implementation.
[src:cat-language/stack-machine] Stack machines have higher code density.
[src:cat-language/stack-machine] In contrast to common stack machine instructions which can easily fit in 6 bits or less, register machines require two or three register-number fields per ALU instruction to select operands; the densest register machines average about 16 bits per instruction plus the operands.
[src:cat-language/stack-machine] Register machines also use a wider offset field for load-store opcodes.
[src:cat-language/stack-machine] A stack machine's compact code naturally fits more instructions in cache, and therefore could achieve better cache efficiency, reducing memory costs or permitting faster memory systems for a given cost.
[src:cat-language/stack-machine] In addition, most stack-machine instructions are very simple, made from only one opcode field or one operand field.
[src:cat-language/stack-machine] Thus, stack-machines require very little electronic resources to decode each instruction.
[src:cat-language/stack-machine] A program has to execute more instructions when compiled to a stack machine than when compiled to a register machine or memory-to-memory machine.
[src:cat-language/stack-machine] Every variable load or constant requires its own separate Load instruction, instead of being bundled within the instruction which uses that value.
[src:cat-language/stack-machine] The separated instructions may be simple and faster running, but the total instruction count is still higher.
[src:cat-language/stack-machine] Most register interpreters specify their registers by number.
[src:cat-language/stack-machine] But a host machine's registers can't be accessed in an indexed array, so a memory array is allotted for virtual registers.
[src:cat-language/stack-machine] Therefore, the instructions of a register interpreter must use memory for passing generated data to the next instruction.
[src:cat-language/stack-machine] This forces register interpreters to be much slower on microprocessors made with a fine process rule (i.e. faster transistors without improving circuit speeds, such as the Haswell x86).
[src:cat-language/stack-machine] These require several clocks for memory access, but only one clock for register access.
[src:cat-language/stack-machine] This may preserve such registers and cache for use in non-flow computation.
[src:cat-language/stack-machine] Some in the industry believe that stack machines execute more data cache cycles for temporary values and local variables than do register machines.
[src:cat-language/stack-machine] On stack machines, temporary values often get spilled into memory, whereas on machines with many registers these temps usually remain in registers.
[src:cat-language/stack-machine] (However, these values often need to be spilled into "activation frames" at the end of a procedure's definition, basic block, or at the very least, into a memory buffer during interrupt processing).
[src:cat-language/stack-machine] Values spilled to memory add more cache cycles.
[src:cat-language/stack-machine] This spilling effect depends on the number of hidden registers used to buffer top-of-stack values, upon the frequency of nested procedure calls, and upon host computer interrupt processing rates.
[src:cat-language/stack-machine] On register machines using optimizing compilers, it is very common for the most-used local variables to remain in registers rather than in stack frame memory cells.
[src:cat-language/stack-machine] This eliminates most data cache cycles for reading and writing those values.
[src:cat-language/stack-machine] The development of "stack scheduling" for performing live-variable analysis, and thus retaining key variables on the stack for extended periods, helps this concern.
[src:cat-language/stack-machine] On the other hand, register machines must spill many of their registers to memory across nested procedure calls.
[src:cat-language/stack-machine] The decision of which registers to spill, and when, is made statically at compile time rather than on the dynamic depth of the calls.
[src:cat-language/stack-machine] This can lead to more data cache traffic than in an advanced stack machine implementation.
[src:cat-language/stack-machine] In register machines, a common subexpression (a subexpression which is used multiple times with the same result value) can be evaluated just once and its result saved in a fast register.
[src:cat-language/stack-machine] The subsequent reuses have no time or code cost, just a register reference.
[src:cat-language/stack-machine] This optimization speeds simple expressions (for example, loading variable X or pointer P) as well as less-common complex expressions.
[src:cat-language/stack-machine] With stack machines, in contrast, results can be stored in one of two ways.
[src:cat-language/stack-machine] Firstly, results can be stored using a temporary variable in memory.
[src:cat-language/stack-machine] Storing and subsequent retrievals cost additional instructions and additional data cache cycles.
[src:cat-language/stack-machine] Doing this is only a win if the subexpression computation costs more in time than fetching from memory, which in most stack CPUs, almost always is the case.
[src:cat-language/stack-machine] It is never worthwhile for simple variables and pointer fetches, because those already have the same cost of one data cache cycle per access.
[src:cat-language/stack-machine] It is only marginally worthwhile for expressions such as `X+1`.
[src:cat-language/stack-machine] These simpler expressions make up the majority of redundant, optimizable expressions in programs written in languages other than concatenative languages.
[src:cat-language/stack-machine] An optimizing compiler can only win on redundancies that the programmer could have avoided in the source code.
[src:cat-language/stack-machine] The second way leaves a computed value on the data stack, duplicating it as needed.
[src:cat-language/stack-machine] This uses operations to copy stack entries.
[src:cat-language/stack-machine] The stack must be depth shallow enough for the CPU's available copy instructions.
[src:cat-language/stack-machine] Hand-written stack code often uses this approach, and achieves speeds like general-purpose register machines.
[src:cat-language/stack-machine] Unfortunately, algorithms for optimal "stack scheduling" are not in wide use by programming languages.
[src:cat-language/stack-machine] In modern machines, the time to fetch a variable from the data cache is often several times longer than the time needed for basic ALU operations.
[src:cat-language/stack-machine] A program runs faster without stalls if its memory loads can be started several cycles before the instruction that needs that variable.
[src:cat-language/stack-machine] Complex machines can do this with a deep pipeline and "out-of-order execution" that examines and runs many instructions at once.
[src:cat-language/stack-machine] Register machines can even do this with much simpler "in-order" hardware, a shallow pipeline, and slightly smarter compilers.
[src:cat-language/stack-machine] The load step becomes a separate instruction, and that instruction is statically scheduled much earlier in the code sequence.
[src:cat-language/stack-machine] The compiler puts independent steps in between.
[src:cat-language/stack-machine] Scheduling memory accesses requires explicit, spare registers.
[src:cat-language/stack-machine] It is not possible on stack machines without exposing some aspect of the micro-architecture to the programmer.
[src:cat-language/stack-machine] For the expression A B −, B must be evaluated and pushed immediately prior to the Minus step.
[src:cat-language/stack-machine] Without stack permutation or hardware multithreading, relatively little useful code can be put in between while waiting for the Load B to finish.
[src:cat-language/stack-machine] Today's increasingly parallel computational loads suggests, however, this might not be the disadvantage it's been made out to be in the past.
[src:cat-language/stack-machine] Stack machines can omit the operand fetching stage of a register machine.
[src:cat-language/stack-machine] For example, in the Java Optimized Processor (JOP) microprocessor the top 2 operands of stack directly enter a data forwarding circuit that is faster than the register file.
[src:cat-language/stack-machine] The Tomasulo algorithm finds instruction-level parallelism by issuing instructions as their data becomes available.
[src:cat-language/stack-machine] Conceptually, the addresses of positions in a stack are no different than the register indexes of a register file.
[src:cat-language/stack-machine] This view permits the out-of-order execution of the Tomasulo algorithm to be used with stack machines.
[src:cat-language/stack-machine] Out-of-order execution in stack machines seems to reduce or avoid many theoretical and practical difficulties.
[src:cat-language/stack-machine] The cited research shows that such a stack machine can exploit instruction-level parallelism, and the resulting hardware must cache data for the instructions.
[src:cat-language/stack-machine] Such machines effectively bypass most memory accesses to the stack.
[src:cat-language/stack-machine] The result achieves throughput (instructions per clock) comparable to load–store architecture machines, with much higher code densities (because operand addresses are implicit).
[src:cat-language/stack-machine] One issue brought up in the research was that it takes about 1.88 stack-machine instructions to do the work of one instruction on a load-store architecture machine.
[src:cat-language/stack-machine] Competitive out-of-order stack machines therefore require about twice as many electronic resources to track instructions ("issue stations").
[src:cat-language/stack-machine] This might be compensated by savings in instruction cache and memory and instruction decoding circuits.
[src:cat-language/stack-machine] Some simple stack machines have a chip design which is fully customized all the way down to the level of individual registers.
[src:cat-language/stack-machine] The top of stack address register and the N top of stack data buffers are built from separate individual register circuits, with separate adders and ad hoc connections.
[src:cat-language/stack-machine] However, most stack machines are built from larger circuit components where the N data buffers are stored together within a register file and share read/write buses.
[src:cat-language/stack-machine] The decoded stack instructions are mapped into one or more sequential actions on that hidden register file.
[src:cat-language/stack-machine] Loads and ALU ops act on a few topmost registers, and implicit spills and fills act on the bottommost registers.
[src:cat-language/stack-machine] The decoder allows the instruction stream to be compact.
[src:cat-language/stack-machine] But if the code stream instead had explicit register-select fields which directly manipulated the underlying register file, the compiler could make better use of all registers and the program would run faster.
[src:cat-language/stack-machine] Microprogrammed stack machines are an example of this.
[src:cat-language/stack-machine] The inner microcode engine is some kind of RISC-like register machine or a VLIW-like machine using multiple register files.
[src:cat-language/stack-machine] When controlled directly by task-specific microcode, that engine gets much more work completed per cycle than when controlled indirectly by equivalent stack code for that same task.
[src:cat-language/stack-machine] The object code translators that translated code for the HP 3000 and Tandem NonStop stack machines to code for the register-based RISC replacements for those machines are another example.
[src:cat-language/stack-machine] They translated stack code sequences into equivalent sequences of RISC code.
[src:cat-language/stack-machine] Minor "local" optimizations removed much of the overhead of a stack architecture.
[src:cat-language/stack-machine] Spare registers were used to factor out repeated address calculations.
[src:cat-language/stack-machine] The translated code still retained plenty of emulation overhead from the mismatch between original and target machines.
[src:cat-language/stack-machine] Despite that burden, the cycle efficiency of the translated code matched the cycle efficiency of the original stack code.
[src:cat-language/stack-machine] And when the source code was recompiled directly to the register machine via optimizing compilers, the efficiency doubled.
[src:cat-language/stack-machine] This shows that the stack architecture and its non-optimizing compilers were wasting over half of the power of the underlying hardware.
[src:cat-language/stack-machine] Register files are good tools for computing because they have high bandwidth and very low latency, compared to memory references via data caches.
[src:cat-language/stack-machine] In a simple machine, the register file allows reading two independent registers and writing of a third, all in one ALU cycle with one-cycle or less latency.
[src:cat-language/stack-machine] Whereas the corresponding data cache can start only one read or one write (not both) per cycle, and the read typically has a latency of two ALU cycles.
[src:cat-language/stack-machine] That's one third of the throughput at twice the pipeline delay.
[src:cat-language/stack-machine] In a complex machine like Athlon that completes two or more instructions per cycle, the register file allows reading of four or more independent registers and writing of two others, all in one ALU cycle with one-cycle latency.
[src:cat-language/stack-machine] Whereas the corresponding dual-ported data cache can start only two reads or writes per cycle, with multiple cycles of latency.
[src:cat-language/stack-machine] Again, that's one third of the throughput of registers.
[src:cat-language/stack-machine] It is very expensive to build a cache with additional ports.
[src:cat-language/stack-machine] Since a stack is a component of most software programs, even when the software used is not strictly a stack machine, a hardware stack machine might more closely mimic the inner workings of its programs.
[src:cat-language/stack-machine] Processor registers have a high thermal cost, and a stack machine might claim higher energy efficiency.
[src:cat-language/stack-machine] Responding to an interrupt involves saving the registers to a stack, and then branching to the interrupt handler code.
[src:cat-language/stack-machine] Often stack machines respond more quickly to interrupts, because most parameters are already on a stack and there is no need to push them there.
[src:cat-language/stack-machine] Some register machines deal with this by having multiple register files that can be instantly swapped but this increases costs and slows down the register file.
[src:cat-language/stack-machine] Interpreters for virtual stack machines are easier to build than interpreters for register machines; the logic for handling memory address modes is in just one place rather than repeated in many instructions.
[src:cat-language/stack-machine] Stack machines also tend to have fewer variations of an opcode; one generalized opcode will handle both frequent cases and obscure corner cases of memory references or function call setup.
[src:cat-language/stack-machine] Interpreters for virtual stack machines are often slower than interpreters for other styles of virtual machine.
[src:cat-language/stack-machine] This slowdown is worst when running on host machines with deep execution pipelines, such as current x86 chips.
[src:cat-language/stack-machine] In some interpreters, the interpreter must execute a N-way switch jump to decode the next opcode and branch to its steps for that particular opcode.
[src:cat-language/stack-machine] Another method for selecting opcodes is threaded code.
[src:cat-language/stack-machine] The host machine's prefetch mechanisms are unable to predict and fetch the target of that indexed or indirect jump.
[src:cat-language/stack-machine] So the host machine's execution pipeline must restart each time the hosted interpreter decodes another virtual instruction.
[src:cat-language/stack-machine] This happens more often for virtual stack machines than for other styles of virtual machine.
[src:cat-language/stack-machine] One example is the Java programming language.
[src:cat-language/stack-machine] Its canonical virtual machine is specified as an 8-bit stack machine.
[src:cat-language/stack-machine] However, the Dalvik virtual machine for Java used on Android smartphones is a 16-bit virtual-register machine—a choice made for efficiency reasons.
[src:cat-language/stack-machine] Arithmetic instructions directly fetch or store local variables via 4-bit (or larger) instruction fields.
[src:cat-language/stack-machine] Similarly version 5.0 of Lua replaced its virtual stack machine with a faster virtual register machine.
[src:cat-language/stack-machine] Since Java virtual machine became popular, microprocessors have employed advanced branch predictors for indirect jumps.
[src:cat-language/stack-machine] This advance avoids most of pipeline restarts from N-way jumps and eliminates much of the instruction count costs that affect stack interpreters.
[src:cat-language/stack-oriented-programming] Stack-based algorithms manipulate data by popping data from and pushing data to the stack.
[src:cat-language/stack-oriented-programming] Operators govern how the stack manipulates data.
[src:cat-language/stack-oriented-programming] To emphasize the effect of a statement, a comment is often used showing the top of the stack before and after the statement; this is known as the stack effect diagram.
[src:cat-language/stack-oriented-programming] Some stack-oriented languages may use multiple stacks for different purposes; for example, PostScript uses separate stacks for variables, dictionaries, procedures, some typical procedures, and control flow statements.
[src:cat-language/stack-oriented-programming] Analysis of the language model allows expressions and programs to be interpreted simply.
[src:cat-language/stack-oriented-programming] PostScript is an example of a postfix stack-based language.
[src:cat-language/stack-oriented-programming] An expression example in this language is `2 3 mul`('mul' being the command for the multiplication operation).
[src:cat-language/stack-oriented-programming] Calculating the expression involves understanding how stack orientation works.
[src:cat-language/stack-oriented-programming] Stack orientation can be presented as the following conveyor belt analogy.
[src:cat-language/stack-oriented-programming] At the end of a conveyor belt (the *input*), plates marked `2`, `3`, and `mul` are placed in sequence.
[src:cat-language/stack-oriented-programming] The plate at the end of the conveyor (`2`) can be taken, however other plates cannot be accessed until the plate at the end is removed.
[src:cat-language/stack-oriented-programming] The plates can only be stored in a stack, and can only be added or removed from atop the stack, not from the middle or bottom.
[src:cat-language/stack-oriented-programming] Blank plates (and a marker) can be supplied and plates can be permanently discarded.
[src:cat-language/stack-oriented-programming] Take plate `2` and put it on the stack, then take plate `3` and put it on the stack.
[src:cat-language/stack-oriented-programming] Then, take the top two plates off the stack, multiply their labels (`2` and `3`), and write the result (`6`) on a new plate.
[src:cat-language/stack-oriented-programming] Discard the two old plates (`2` and `3`) and the plate `mul`, and put the new plate on the stack.
[src:cat-language/stack-oriented-programming] With no more plates remaining on the conveyor, the result of the calculation (`6`) is shown on the plate atop the stack.
[src:cat-language/stack-oriented-programming] What if a more complex calculation is needed, such as `(2 + 3) × 11 + 1`?
[src:cat-language/stack-oriented-programming] If it is first written in postfix form, that is, `2 3 add 11 mul 1 add`, the calculation can be performed in exactly the same manner and achieve the correct result.
[src:cat-language/stack-oriented-programming] The steps of the calculation are shown in the table below.
[src:cat-language/stack-oriented-programming] Each column shows an input element (the plate at the end of the conveyor), and the contents of the stack after processing that input.
[src:cat-language/stack-oriented-programming] After processing all the input, the stack contains `56`, which is the answer.
[src:cat-language/stack-oriented-programming] From this, the following can be concluded: a stack-based programming language has only one way to handle data, by taking one piece of data from atop the stack, termed *pop*ping, and putting data back atop the stack, termed *push*ing.
[src:cat-language/stack-oriented-programming] Any expression that can be written *conventionally*, or in another programming language, can be written in postfix (or prefix) form and thus be amenable to being interpreted by a stack-oriented language.
[src:cat-language/stack-oriented-programming] Since the stack is the key means to manipulate data in a stack-oriented language, such languages often provide some sort of stack manipulation operators.
[src:cat-language/stack-oriented-programming] These become key in studying procedures.
[src:cat-language/stack-oriented-programming] As an aid to understanding the effect of the statement, a short comment is used showing the top of the stack before and after the statement.
[src:cat-language/stack-oriented-programming] The top of the stack is rightmost if there are multiple items.
[src:cat-language/stack-oriented-programming] This notation is commonly used in the Forth language, where comments are enclosed in parentheses.
[src:cat-language/stack-oriented-programming] It is equivalent to preconditions and postconditions in Hoare logic.
[src:cat-language/stack-oriented-programming] Both comments may also be referenced as assertions, though not necessarily in the context of Stack-based languages.
[src:cat-language/stack-oriented-programming] PostScript and some other stack languages have other separate stacks for other purposes.
[src:cat-language/stack-oriented-programming] The evaluation of different expressions has already been analysed.
[src:cat-language/stack-oriented-programming] The implementation of variables is important for any programming language, but for stack-oriented languages, it is of special concern, as there is only one way to interact with data.
[src:cat-language/stack-oriented-programming] The way variables are implemented in stack-oriented languages such as PostScript usually involves a separate, specialized stack which holds *dictionaries* of key-value pairs.
[src:cat-language/stack-oriented-programming] To create a variable, a key (the variable name) must be created first, with which a value is then associated.
[src:cat-language/stack-oriented-programming] In PostScript, a name data object is prefixed with a `/`, so `/x` is a name data object which can be associated with, for example, the number `42`.
[src:cat-language/stack-oriented-programming] associates with the name `x` with the number `42` in the dictionary atop the stack.
[src:cat-language/stack-oriented-programming] A difference exists between `/x` and `x` – the former is a data object representing a name, and `x` stands for what is defined under `/x`.
[src:cat-language/stack-oriented-programming] A procedure in a stack-based programming language is treated as a data object in its own right.
[src:cat-language/stack-oriented-programming] In PostScript, procedures are denoted between `{` and `}`.
[src:cat-language/stack-oriented-programming] represents an anonymous procedure to duplicate what is on the top of the stack and then multiply the result – a squaring procedure.
[src:cat-language/stack-oriented-programming] Since procedures are treated as simple data objects, names with procedures can be defined.
[src:cat-language/stack-oriented-programming] When they are retrieved, they are executed directly.
[src:cat-language/stack-oriented-programming] Dictionaries provide a means of controlling scoping, as well as storing definitions.
[src:cat-language/stack-oriented-programming] Since data objects are stored in the top-most dictionary, an unexpected ability arises naturally: when looking up a definition from a dictionary, the topmost dictionary is checked, then the next, and so on.
[src:cat-language/stack-oriented-programming] If a procedure is defined that has the same name as another already defined in a different dictionary, the local one will be called.
[src:cat-language/stack-oriented-programming] They are handled by the procedure in a very specific way, different from that of other programming languages.
[src:cat-language/stack-oriented-programming] A recursive definition is used on the stack.
[src:cat-language/stack-oriented-programming] The Fibonacci number function takes one argument.
[src:cat-language/stack-oriented-programming] Since the expression evaluates to true, the inner procedure is evaluated.
[src:cat-language/stack-oriented-programming] This procedure does not use named variables, purely the stack.
[src:cat-language/stack-oriented-programming] Named variables can be created by using the `/a exch def` construct.
[src:cat-language/stack-oriented-programming] is a squaring procedure with a named variable `n`.
[src:cat-language/stack-oriented-programming] As there exist anonymous procedures, flow control can arise naturally.
[src:cat-language/stack-oriented-programming] Three pieces of data are required for an if-then-else statement: a condition, a procedure to be done if the condition is true, and one to be done if the condition is false.
[src:cat-language/stack-oriented-programming] Looping and other constructs are similar.
[src:cat-language/stack-oriented-programming] The simple model provided in a stack-oriented language allows expressions and programs to be interpreted simply and theoretically evaluated much faster, since no syntax analysis needs to be done but lexical analysis.
[src:cat-language/stack-oriented-programming] The way such programs are written facilitates being interpreted by machines, which is why PostScript suits printers well for its use.
[src:cat-language/stack-oriented-programming] However, the slightly artificial way of writing PostScript programs can form an initial barrier to understanding stack-oriented languages such as PostScript.
[src:cat-language/stack-oriented-programming] While the ability to shadow by overriding inbuilt and other definitions can make programs hard to debug, and irresponsible use of this feature can cause unpredictable behaviour, it can simplify some functions greatly.
[src:cat-language/stack-oriented-programming] For example, in PostScript use, the `showpage` operator can be overridden with a custom one that applies a certain style to the page, instead of having to define a custom operator or repeat code to generate the style.
[src:cat-language/type-inference] In type theory, **type inference** (sometimes called **type reconstruction**) is the automatic detection of the type of an expression.
[src:cat-language/type-inference] These include programming languages and mathematical type systems, but also natural languages in some branches of computer science and linguistics.
[src:cat-language/type-inference] In a typed language, a term's type determines the ways it can and cannot be used in that language.
[src:cat-language/type-inference] At best it might be metaphor; bending type rules is a feature of poetic language.
[src:cat-language/type-inference] A term's type can also affect the interpretation of operations involving that term.
[src:cat-language/type-inference] For instance, "a song" is of composable type, so we interpret it as the thing created in the phrase "write a song".
[src:cat-language/type-inference] On the other hand, "a friend" is of recipient type, so we interpret it as the addressee in the phrase "write a friend".
[src:cat-language/type-inference] In normal language, we would be surprised if "write a song" meant addressing a letter to a song or "write a friend" meant drafting a friend on paper.
[src:cat-language/type-inference] Terms with different types can even refer to materially the same thing.
[src:cat-language/type-inference] For example, we would interpret "to hang up the clothes line" as putting it into use, but "to hang up the leash" as putting it away, even though, in context, both "clothes line" and "leash" might refer the same rope, just at different times.
[src:cat-language/type-inference] Typings are often used to prevent an object from being considered too generally.
[src:cat-language/type-inference] For instance, if the type system treats all numbers as the same, then a programmer who accidentally writes code where `4` is supposed to mean "4 seconds" but is interpreted as "4 meters" would have no warning of their mistake until it caused problems at runtime.
[src:cat-language/type-inference] By incorporating units into the type system, these mistakes can be detected much earlier.
[src:cat-language/type-inference] As another example, Russell's paradox arises when anything can be a set element and any predicate can define a set, but more careful typing gives several ways to resolve the paradox.
[src:cat-language/type-inference] In fact, Russell's paradox sparked early versions of type theory.
[src:cat-language/type-inference] Especially in programming languages, there may not be much shared background knowledge available to the computer.
[src:cat-language/type-inference] In manifestly typed languages, this means that most types have to be declared explicitly.
[src:cat-language/type-inference] Type inference aims to alleviate this burden, freeing the author from declaring types that the computer should be able to deduce from context.
[src:cat-language/type-inference] In a typing, an expression E is opposed to a type T, formally written as E : T.
[src:cat-language/type-inference] Usually a typing only makes sense within some context, which is omitted here.
[src:cat-language/type-inference] If there is a way to derive a type for E, then we have accomplished *type inference*.
[src:cat-language/type-inference] Given only a type, is there any expression for it or does the type have no values?
[src:cat-language/type-inference] For the simply typed lambda calculus, all three questions are decidable.
[src:cat-language/type-inference] The situation is not as comfortable when more expressive types are allowed.
[src:cat-language/type-inference] Types are a feature present in some strongly statically typed languages.
[src:cat-language/type-inference] It is often characteristic of functional programming languages in general.
[src:cat-language/type-inference] The majority of them use a simple form of type inference; the Hindley–Milner type system can provide more complete type inference.
[src:cat-language/type-inference] The ability to infer types automatically makes many programming tasks easier, leaving the programmer free to omit type annotations while still permitting type checking.
[src:cat-language/type-inference] In some programming languages, all values have a data type explicitly declared at compile time, limiting the values a particular expression can take on at run-time.
[src:cat-language/type-inference] Increasingly, just-in-time compilation blurs the distinction between run time and compile time.
[src:cat-language/type-inference] However, historically, if the type of a value is known only at run-time, these languages are dynamically typed.
[src:cat-language/type-inference] In other languages, the type of an expression is known only at compile time; these languages are statically typed.
[src:cat-language/type-inference] In most statically typed languages, the input and output types of functions and local variables ordinarily must be explicitly provided by type annotations.
[src:cat-language/type-inference] The signature of this function definition, `int increment(int x)`, declares that `increment()` is a function that takes one argument, an integer, and returns an integer.
[src:cat-language/type-inference] `int result;` declares that the local variable `result` is an integer.
[src:cat-language/type-inference] This is identical to how code is written in the language Dart, except that it is subject to some added constraints as described below.
[src:cat-language/type-inference] It would be possible to *infer* the types of all the variables at compile time.
[src:cat-language/type-inference] In the example above, the compiler would infer that `result` and `x` have type integer since the constant `1` is type integer, and hence that `increment()` is a function `int -> int`.
[src:cat-language/type-inference] The variable `result2` isn't used in a legal manner, so it wouldn't have a type.
[src:cat-language/type-inference] In the imaginary language in which the last example is written, the compiler would assume that, in the absence of information to the contrary, `+` takes two integers and returns one integer.
[src:cat-language/type-inference] (This is how it works in, for example, OCaml.) From this, the type inferencer can infer that the type of `x + 1` is an integer, which means `result` is an integer and thus the return value of `add_one` is an integer.
[src:cat-language/type-inference] Similarly, since `+` requires both of its arguments be of the same type, `x` must be an integer, and thus, `add_one` accepts one integer as an argument.
[src:cat-language/type-inference] However, in the subsequent line, `result2` is calculated by adding a decimal `1.0` with floating-point arithmetic, causing a conflict in the use of `x` for both integer and floating-point expressions.
[src:cat-language/type-inference] The correct type-inference algorithm for such a situation has been known since 1958 and has been known to be correct since 1982.
[src:cat-language/type-inference] It revisits the prior inferences and uses the most general type from the outset: in this case floating-point.
[src:cat-language/type-inference] This can however have detrimental implications, for instance using a floating-point from the outset can introduce precision issues that would have not been there with an integer type.
[src:cat-language/type-inference] Frequently, however, degenerate type-inference algorithms are used that cannot backtrack and instead generate an error message in such a situation.
[src:cat-language/type-inference] This behavior may be preferable as type inference may not always be neutral algorithmically, as illustrated by the prior floating-point precision issue.
[src:cat-language/type-inference] An algorithm of intermediate generality implicitly declares `result2` as a floating-point variable, and the addition implicitly converts `x` to a floating point.
[src:cat-language/type-inference] This can be correct if the calling contexts never supply a floating point argument.
[src:cat-language/type-inference] Such a situation shows the difference between *type inference*, which does not involve type conversion, and implicit type conversion, which forces data to a different data type, often without restrictions.
[src:cat-language/type-inference] Finally, a significant downside of complex type-inference algorithm is that the resulting type inference resolution is not going to be obvious to humans (notably because of the backtracking), which can be detrimental as code is primarily intended to be comprehensible to humans.
[src:cat-language/type-inference] The recent emergence of just-in-time compilation allows for hybrid approaches where the type of arguments supplied by the various calling context is known at compile time, and can generate a large number of compiled versions of the same function.
[src:cat-language/type-inference] Each compiled version can then be optimized for a different set of types.
[src:cat-language/type-inference] A version that accepts an integer input and uses implicit type conversion.
[src:cat-language/type-inference] A version that accepts a floating-point number as input and uses floating point instructions throughout.
[src:cat-language/type-inference] Type inference is the ability to automatically deduce, either partially or fully, the type of an expression at compile time.
[src:cat-language/type-inference] The compiler is often able to infer the type of a variable or the type signature of a function, without explicit type annotations having been given.
[src:cat-language/type-inference] In many cases, it is possible to omit type annotations from a program completely if the type inference system is robust enough, or the program or language is simple enough.
[src:cat-language/type-inference] It is through recognition of the eventual reduction of expressions to implicitly typed atomic values that the compiler for a type inferring language is able to compile a program completely without type annotations.
[src:cat-language/type-inference] In complex forms of higher-order programming and polymorphism, it is not always possible for the compiler to infer as much, and type annotations are occasionally necessary for disambiguation.
[src:cat-language/type-inference] For instance, type inference with polymorphic recursion is known to be undecidable.
[src:cat-language/type-inference] Furthermore, explicit type annotations can be used to optimize code by forcing the compiler to use a more specific (faster/smaller) type than it had inferred.
[src:cat-language/type-inference] Some methods for type inference are based on constraint satisfaction or satisfiability modulo theories.
[src:cat-language/type-inference] (Recall that `:` in Haskell denotes cons, structuring a head element and a list tail into a bigger list or destructuring a nonempty list into its head element and its tail.
[src:cat-language/type-inference] Type inference on the `map` function proceeds as follows.
[src:cat-language/type-inference] `map` is a function of two arguments, so its type is constrained to be of the form `a -> b -> c`.
[src:cat-language/type-inference] In Haskell, the patterns `[]` and `(first:rest)` always match lists, so the second argument must be a list type: `b = [d]` for some type `d`.
[src:cat-language/type-inference] Its first argument `f` is applied to the argument `first`, which must have type `d`, corresponding with the type in the list argument, so `f :: d -> e` (`::` means "is of type") for some type `e`.
[src:cat-language/type-inference] The return value of `map f`, finally, is a list of whatever `f` produces, so `[e]`.
[src:cat-language/type-inference] Putting the parts together leads to `map :: (d -> e) -> [d] -> [e]`.
[src:cat-language/type-inference] It turns out that this is also the most general type, since no further constraints apply.
[src:cat-language/type-inference] As the inferred type of `map` is parametrically polymorphic, the type of the arguments and results of `f` are not inferred, but left as type variables, and so `map` can be applied to functions and lists of various types, as long as the actual types match in each invocation.
[src:cat-language/type-inference] The algorithms used by programs like compilers are equivalent to the informally structured reasoning above, but a bit more verbose and methodical.
[src:cat-language/type-inference] The exact details depend on the inference algorithm chosen (see the following section for the best-known algorithm), but the example below gives the general idea.
[src:cat-language/type-inference] We also constrain the left and right sides of each equation to unify with each other: `κ ~ [δ]` and `μ ~ ο`.
[src:cat-language/type-inference] Then we substitute until no further variables can be eliminated.
[src:cat-language/type-inference] The exact order is immaterial; if the code type-checks, any order will lead to the same final form.
[src:cat-language/type-inference] No more substitutions are possible, and relabeling gives us `map :: (a -> b) -> [a] -> [b]`, the same as we found without going into these details.
[src:cat-language/type-inference] The algorithm first used to perform type inference is now informally termed the Hindley–Milner algorithm, although the algorithm should properly be attributed to Damas and Milner.
[src:cat-language/type-inference] It is also traditionally called *type reconstruction*.
[src:cat-language/type-inference] If a term is well-typed in accordance with Hindley–Milner typing rules, then the rules generate a principal typing for the term.
[src:cat-language/type-inference] The process of discovering this principal typing is the process of "reconstruction".
[src:cat-language/type-inference] The origin of this algorithm is the type inference algorithm for the simply typed lambda calculus that was devised by Haskell Curry and Robert Feys in 1958.
[src:cat-language/type-inference] Roger Hindley extended this work and proved that their algorithm always inferred the most general type.
[src:cat-language/type-inference] In 1978 Robin Milner, independently of Hindley's work, provided an equivalent algorithm, Algorithm W.
[src:cat-language/type-inference] In 1982 Luis Damas finally proved that Milner's algorithm is complete and extended it to support systems with polymorphic references.
[src:cat-language/type-inference] By design, type inference will infer the most general type appropriate.
[src:cat-language/type-inference] However, many languages, especially older programming languages, have slightly unsound type systems, where using a more general types may not always be algorithmically neutral.
[src:cat-language/type-inference] Type inference algorithms have been used to analyze natural languages as well as programming languages.
[src:cat-language/type-inference] Type inference algorithms are also used in some grammar induction and constraint-based grammar systems for natural languages.
[src:cat-language/type-system] A programming language consists of a system of allowed sequences of symbols (constructs) together with rules that define how each construct is interpreted.
[src:cat-language/type-system] For example, a language might allow expressions representing various types of data, expressions that provide structuring rules for data, expressions representing various operations on data, and constructs that provide sequencing rules for the order in which to perform operations.
[src:cat-language/type-system] A simple type system for a programming language is a set of rules that associates a *data type* (for example, integer, floating point, string) with each *term* (data-valued expression) in a computer program.
[src:cat-language/type-system] In more ambitious type systems, a variety of constructs, such as variables, expressions, functions, and modules, may be assigned types.
[src:cat-language/type-system] Type systems formalize and enforce the otherwise implicit categories the programmer uses for algebraic data types, data structures, or other data types, such as "string", "array of float", "function returning boolean".
[src:cat-language/type-system] The main purpose of a type system in a programming language is to reduce possibilities for bugs in computer programs due to mismatches in how values are interpreted in different parts of a program.
[src:cat-language/type-system] The aim is to prevent operations expecting a certain kind of value from being applied to values for which that operation does not make sense (validity errors).
[src:cat-language/type-system] A type system can detect and prevent some of these mismatches.
[src:cat-language/type-system] When a type mismatch is detected, it is called a type error.
[src:cat-language/type-system] The type of a term constrains the contexts in which it may be used.
[src:cat-language/type-system] For a variable, the type system determines the allowed values of that variable.
[src:cat-language/type-system] For that variable to be presented as a parameter to an operation, the operation must be able to accept in that parameter any value that the type of the variable allows.
[src:cat-language/type-system] Type systems are typically specified as part of programming language design.
[src:cat-language/type-system] They are built into interpreters and compilers for the language.
[src:cat-language/type-system] In some languages, the type system can be extended by optional tools that perform added checks using the language's original type syntax and grammar.
[src:cat-language/type-system] Type systems allow defining interfaces between different parts of a computer program, and then checking that the parts have been connected in a consistent way.
[src:cat-language/type-system] This checking can happen statically (at compile time), dynamically (at runtime), or as a combination of both.
[src:cat-language/type-system] Type systems have other purposes as well, such as expressing business rules, enabling certain compiler optimizations, allowing for multiple dispatch, and providing a form of documentation.
[src:cat-language/type-system] An example of a simple type system is that of the C language.
[src:cat-language/type-system] The portions of a C program are the function definitions.
[src:cat-language/type-system] One function is invoked by another function.
[src:cat-language/type-system] The interface of a function states the name of the function and a list of parameters that are passed to the function's code.
[src:cat-language/type-system] The code of an invoking function states the name of the invoked, along with the names of variables that hold values to pass to it.
[src:cat-language/type-system] During a computer program's execution, the values are placed into temporary storage, then execution jumps to the code of the invoked function.
[src:cat-language/type-system] The invoked function's code accesses the values and makes use of them.
[src:cat-language/type-system] If the instructions inside the function are written with the assumption of receiving an integer value, but the calling code passed a floating-point value, then the wrong result will be computed by the invoked function.
[src:cat-language/type-system] The C compiler checks the types of the arguments passed to a function when it is called against the types of the parameters declared in the function's definition.
[src:cat-language/type-system] If the types do not match, the compiler throws a compile-time error or warning.
[src:cat-language/type-system] A compiler may also use the static type of a value to optimize the storage it needs and the choice of algorithms for operations on the value.
[src:cat-language/type-system] In many C compilers the *float* data type, for example, is represented in 32 bits, in accord with the IEEE specification for single-precision floating point numbers.
[src:cat-language/type-system] They will thus use floating-point-specific microprocessor operations on those values (floating-point addition, multiplication, etc.).
[src:cat-language/type-system] The depth of type constraints and the manner of their evaluation affect the *typing* of the language.
[src:cat-language/type-system] A programming language may further associate an operation with various resolutions for each type, in the case of type polymorphism.
[src:cat-language/type-system] Type theory is the study of type systems.
[src:cat-language/type-system] The concrete types of some programming languages, such as integers and strings, depend on practical issues of computer architecture, compiler implementation, and language design.
[src:cat-language/type-system] Formally, type theory studies type systems.
[src:cat-language/type-system] A programming language must have the opportunity to type check using the *type system* whether at compile time or runtime, manually annotated or automatically inferred.
[src:cat-language/type-system] Assigning a data type, termed *typing*, gives meaning to a sequence of bits such as a value in memory or some object such as a variable.
[src:cat-language/type-system] Associating a sequence of bits with a type conveys that meaning to the programmable hardware to form a *symbolic system* composed of that hardware and some program.
[src:cat-language/type-system] A program associates each value with at least one specific type, but it also can occur that one value is associated with many subtypes.
[src:cat-language/type-system] Other entities, such as objects, modules, communication channels, and dependencies can become associated with a type.
[src:cat-language/type-system] Even a type can become associated with a type.
[src:cat-language/type-system] An implementation of a *type system* could in theory associate identifications called *data type* (a type of a value), *class* (a type of an object), and *kind* (a *type of a type*, or metatype).
[src:cat-language/type-system] These are the abstractions that typing can go through, on a hierarchy of levels contained in a system.
[src:cat-language/type-system] It is challenging to find a sufficiently expressive type system that satisfies all programming practices in a type safe manner.
[src:cat-language/type-system] A programming language compiler can also implement a *dependent type* or an *effect system*, which enables even more program specifications to be verified by a type checker.
[src:cat-language/type-system] Beyond simple value-type pairs, a virtual "region" of code is associated with an "effect" component describing *what* is being done *with what*, and enabling for example to "throw" an error report.
[src:cat-language/type-system] Thus the symbolic system may be a *type and effect system*, which endows it with more safety checking than type checking alone.
[src:cat-language/type-system] Whether automated by the compiler or specified by a programmer, a type system renders program behavior illegal if it falls outside the type-system rules.
[src:cat-language/type-system] A type error occurs when an operation receives a different type of data than it expected.
[src:cat-language/type-system] For example, a type error would happen if a line of code divides two integers, and is passed a string of letters instead of an integer.
[src:cat-language/type-system] It is an unintended condition which might manifest in multiple stages of a program's development.
[src:cat-language/type-system] Thus a facility for detection of the error is needed in the type system.
[src:cat-language/type-system] In some languages, such as Haskell, for which type inference is automated, lint might be available to its compiler to aid in the detection of error.
[src:cat-language/type-system] Type safety contributes to program correctness, but might only guarantee correctness at the cost of making the type checking itself an undecidable problem (as in the halting problem).
[src:cat-language/type-system] In a *type system* with automated type checking, a program may prove to run incorrectly yet produce no compiler errors.
[src:cat-language/type-system] Division by zero is an unsafe and incorrect operation, but a type checker which only runs at compile time does not scan for division by zero in most languages; that division would surface as a runtime error.
[src:cat-language/type-system] To prove the absence of these defects, other kinds of formal methods, collectively known as program analyses, are in common use.
[src:cat-language/type-system] Alternatively, a sufficiently expressive type system, such as in dependently typed languages, can prevent these kinds of errors (for example, expressing *the type of non-zero numbers*).
[src:cat-language/type-system] In addition, software testing is an empirical method for finding errors that such a type checker would not detect.
[src:cat-language/type-system] The process of verifying and enforcing the constraints of types, *type checking*, may occur at compile time (a static check) or at runtime (a dynamic check).
[src:cat-language/type-system] If a language specification requires its typing rules strongly, more or less allowing only those automatic type conversions that do not lose information, one can refer to the process as *strongly typed*; if not, as *weakly typed*.
[src:cat-language/type-system] The terms are not usually used in a strict sense.
[src:cat-language/type-system] Static type checking is the process of verifying the type safety of a program based on analysis of a program's text (source code).
[src:cat-language/type-system] If a program passes a static type checker, then the program is guaranteed to satisfy some set of type safety properties for all possible inputs.
[src:cat-language/type-system] Static type checking can be considered a limited form of program verification (see type safety), and in a type-safe language, can also be considered an optimization.
[src:cat-language/type-system] If a compiler can prove that a program is well-typed, then it does not need to emit dynamic safety checks, allowing the resulting compiled binary to run faster and to be smaller.
[src:cat-language/type-system] Static type checking for Turing-complete languages is inherently conservative.
[src:cat-language/type-system] Even if the expression `<complex test>` always evaluates to `true` at runtime, most type checkers will reject the program as ill-typed, because it is difficult (if not impossible) for a static analyzer to determine that the `else` branch will not be taken.
[src:cat-language/type-system] Consequently, a static type checker will quickly detect type errors in rarely used code paths.
[src:cat-language/type-system] Without static type checking, even code coverage tests with 100% coverage may be unable to find such type errors.
[src:cat-language/type-system] The tests may fail to detect such type errors, because the combination of all places where values are created and all places where a certain value is used must be taken into account.
[src:cat-language/type-system] A number of useful and common programming language features cannot be checked statically, such as downcasting.
[src:cat-language/type-system] Thus, many languages will have both static and dynamic type checking; the static type checker verifies what it can, and dynamic checks verify the rest.
[src:cat-language/type-system] Many languages with static type checking provide a way to bypass the type checker.
[src:cat-language/type-system] Some languages allow programmers to choose between static and dynamic type safety.
[src:cat-language/type-system] For example, historically C# declares variables statically, but C# 4.0 introduces the `dynamic` keyword, which is used to declare variables to be checked dynamically at runtime.
[src:cat-language/type-system] Other languages allow writing code that is not type-safe; for example, in C, programmers can freely cast a value between any two types that have the same size, effectively subverting the type concept.
[src:cat-language/type-system] Dynamic type checking is the process of verifying the type safety of a program at runtime.
[src:cat-language/type-system] Implementations of dynamically type-checked languages generally associate each runtime object with a *type tag* (i.e., a reference to a type) containing its type information.
[src:cat-language/type-system] This runtime type information (RTTI) can also be used to implement dynamic dispatch, late binding, downcasting, reflective programming (reflection), and similar features.
[src:cat-language/type-system] Most type-safe languages include some form of dynamic type checking, even if they also have a static type checker.
[src:cat-language/type-system] The reason for this is that many useful features or properties are difficult or impossible to verify statically.
[src:cat-language/type-system] For example, suppose that a program defines two types, A and B, where B is a subtype of A.
[src:cat-language/type-system] If the program tries to convert a value of type A to type B, which is known as downcasting, then the operation is legal only if the value being converted is actually a value of type B.
[src:cat-language/type-system] Thus, a dynamic check is needed to verify that the operation is safe.
[src:cat-language/type-system] This requirement is one of the criticisms of downcasting.
[src:cat-language/type-system] By definition, dynamic type checking may cause a program to fail at runtime.
[src:cat-language/type-system] In some programming languages, it is possible to anticipate and recover from these failures.
[src:cat-language/type-system] In others, type-checking errors are considered fatal.
[src:cat-language/type-system] Programming languages that include dynamic type checking but not static type checking are often called "dynamically typed programming languages".
[src:cat-language/type-system] Certain languages allow both static and dynamic typing.
[src:cat-language/type-system] For example, Java and some other ostensibly statically typed languages support downcasting types to their subtypes, querying an object to discover its dynamic type and other type operations that depend on runtime type information.
[src:cat-language/type-system] More generally, most programming languages include mechanisms for dispatching over different 'kinds' of data, such as disjoint unions, runtime polymorphism, and variant types.
[src:cat-language/type-system] Even when not interacting with type annotations or type checking, such mechanisms are materially similar to dynamic typing implementations.
[src:cat-language/type-system] Objects in object-oriented languages are usually accessed by a reference whose static target type (or manifest type) is equal to either the object's runtime type (its latent type) or a supertype thereof.
[src:cat-language/type-system] This is conformant with the Liskov substitution principle, which states that all operations performed on an instance of a given type can also be performed on an instance of a subtype.
[src:cat-language/type-system] This concept is also known as subsumption or subtype polymorphism.
[src:cat-language/type-system] In some languages subtypes may also possess covariant or contravariant return types and argument types respectively.
[src:cat-language/type-system] Certain languages, for example Clojure, Common Lisp, or Cython are dynamically type checked by default, but allow programs to opt into static type checking by providing optional annotations.
[src:cat-language/type-system] One reason to use such hints would be to optimize the performance of critical sections of a program.
[src:cat-language/type-system] The programming environment *DrRacket*, a pedagogic environment based on Lisp, and a precursor of the language Racket is also soft-typed.
[src:cat-language/type-system] Conversely, as of version 4.0, the C# language provides a way to indicate that a variable should not be statically type checked.
[src:cat-language/type-system] A variable whose type is `dynamic` will not be subject to static type checking.
[src:cat-language/type-system] Instead, the program relies on runtime type information to determine how the variable may be used.
[src:cat-language/type-system] In Rust, the `dyn std::any::Any` trait object provides dynamic typing of types containing no or only `'static` lifetimes.
[src:cat-language/type-system] The choice between static and dynamic typing requires certain trade-offs.
[src:cat-language/type-system] Static typing can find type errors reliably at compile time, which increases the reliability of the delivered program.
[src:cat-language/type-system] However, programmers disagree over how commonly type errors occur, resulting in further disagreements over the proportion of those bugs that are coded that would be caught by appropriately representing the designed types in code.
[src:cat-language/type-system] Static typing advocates believe programs are more reliable when they have been well type-checked, whereas dynamic-typing advocates point to distributed code that has proven reliable and to small bug databases.
[src:cat-language/type-system] The value of static typing increases as the strength of the type system is increased.
[src:cat-language/type-system] Advocates of dependent typing, implemented in languages such as Dependent ML and Epigram, have suggested that almost all bugs can be considered type errors, if the types used in a program are properly declared by the programmer or correctly inferred by the compiler.
[src:cat-language/type-system] Static typing usually results in compiled code that executes faster.
[src:cat-language/type-system] When the compiler knows the exact data types that are in use (which is necessary for static verification, either through declaration or inference) it can produce optimized machine code.
[src:cat-language/type-system] Some dynamically typed languages such as Common Lisp allow optional type declarations for optimization for this reason.
[src:cat-language/type-system] By contrast, dynamic typing may allow compilers to run faster and interpreters to dynamically load new code, because changes to source code in dynamically typed languages may result in less checking to perform and less code to revisit.
[src:cat-language/type-system] This too may reduce the edit-compile-test-debug cycle.
[src:cat-language/type-system] Statically typed languages that lack type inference (such as C and Java prior to version 10) require that programmers declare the types that a method or function must use.
[src:cat-language/type-system] This can serve as added program documentation, that is active and dynamic, instead of static.
[src:cat-language/type-system] This allows a compiler to prevent it from drifting out of synchrony, and from being ignored by programmers.
[src:cat-language/type-system] However, a language can be statically typed without requiring type declarations (examples include Haskell, Scala, OCaml, F#, Swift, and to a lesser extent C# and C++), so explicit type declaration is not required for static typing in all languages.
[src:cat-language/type-system] Dynamic typing allows constructs that some (simple) static type checking would reject as illegal.
[src:cat-language/type-system] For example, *eval* functions, which execute arbitrary data as code, become possible.
[src:cat-language/type-system] An *eval* function is possible with static typing, but requires advanced uses of algebraic data types.
[src:cat-language/type-system] Further, dynamic typing better accommodates transitional code and prototyping, such as allowing a placeholder data structure (mock object) to be transparently used in place of a full data structure (usually for the purposes of experimentation and testing).
[src:cat-language/type-system] Dynamic typing typically allows duck typing (which enables easier code reuse).
[src:cat-language/type-system] Many languages with static typing also feature duck typing or other mechanisms like generic programming that also enable easier code reuse.
[src:cat-language/type-system] Dynamic typing typically makes metaprogramming easier to use.
[src:cat-language/type-system] For example, C++ templates are typically more cumbersome to write than the equivalent Ruby or Python code since C++ has stronger rules regarding type definitions (for both functions and variables).
[src:cat-language/type-system] This forces a developer to write more boilerplate code for a template than a Python developer would need to.
[src:cat-language/type-system] More advanced runtime constructs such as metaclasses and introspection are often harder to use in statically typed languages.
[src:cat-language/type-system] In some languages, such features may also be used e.g. to generate new types and behaviors on the fly, based on runtime data.
[src:cat-language/type-system] Such advanced constructs are often provided by dynamic programming languages; many of these are dynamically typed, although *dynamic typing* need not be related to *dynamic programming languages*.
[src:cat-language/type-system] Languages are often colloquially referred to as *strongly typed* or *weakly typed*.
[src:cat-language/type-system] In fact, there is no universally accepted definition of what these terms mean.
[src:cat-language/type-system] In general, there are more precise terms to represent the differences between type systems that lead people to call them "strong" or "weak".
[src:cat-language/type-system] A third way of categorizing the type system of a programming language is by the safety of typed operations and conversions.
[src:cat-language/type-system] Computer scientists use the term *type-safe language* to describe languages that do not allow operations or conversions that violate the rules of the type system.
[src:cat-language/type-system] Computer scientists use the term *memory-safe language* (or just *safe language*) to describe languages that do not allow programs to access memory that has not been assigned for their use.
[src:cat-language/type-system] For example, a memory-safe language will check array bounds, or else statically guarantee (i.e., at compile time before execution) that array accesses out of the array boundaries will cause compile-time and perhaps runtime errors.
[src:cat-language/type-system] In this example, the variable `z` will have the value 42.
[src:cat-language/type-system] Although this may not be what the programmer anticipated, it is a well-defined result.
[src:cat-language/type-system] If `y` were a different string, one that could not be converted to a number (e.g., "Hello, World"), the result would be well-defined also.
[src:cat-language/type-system] A program can be type-safe or memory-safe and still crash on an invalid operation.
[src:cat-language/type-system] This is for languages where the type system is not sufficiently advanced to precisely specify the validity of operations on all possible operands.
[src:cat-language/type-system] But if a program encounters an operation that is not type-safe, terminating the program is often the only option.
[src:cat-language/type-system] In this example `z` will point to a memory address five characters beyond `y`, equivalent to three characters after the terminating zero character of the string pointed to by `y`.
[src:cat-language/type-system] This is memory that the program is not expected to access.
[src:cat-language/type-system] In C terms this is simply undefined behaviour and the program may do anything; with a simple compiler it might actually print whatever byte is stored after the string "37".
[src:cat-language/type-system] As this example shows, C is not memory-safe.
[src:cat-language/type-system] As arbitrary data was assumed to be a character, it is also not a type-safe language.
[src:cat-language/type-system] In general, type-safety and memory-safety go hand in hand.
[src:cat-language/type-system] For example, a language that supports pointer arithmetic and number-to-pointer conversions (like C) is neither memory-safe nor type-safe, because it allows arbitrary memory to be accessed as if it were valid memory of any type.
[src:cat-language/type-system] Some languages allow different levels of checking to apply to different regions of code.
[src:cat-language/type-system] Additional tools such as lint and IBM Rational Purify can also be used to achieve a higher level of strictness.
[src:cat-language/type-system] It has been proposed, chiefly by Gilad Bracha, that the choice of type system be made independent of choice of language; that a type system should be a module that can be *plugged* into a language as needed.
[src:cat-language/type-system] He believes this is advantageous, because what he calls mandatory type systems make languages less expressive and code more fragile.
[src:cat-language/type-system] The requirement that the type system does not affect the semantics of the language is difficult to fulfill.
[src:cat-language/type-system] Optional typing is related to, but distinct from, gradual typing.
[src:cat-language/type-system] While both typing disciplines can be used to perform static analysis of code (static typing), optional type systems do not enforce type safety at runtime (dynamic typing).
[src:cat-language/type-system] The term *polymorphism* refers to the ability of code (especially, functions or classes) to act on values of multiple types, or to the ability of different instances of the same data structure to contain elements of different types.
[src:cat-language/type-system] Type systems that allow polymorphism generally do so to improve the potential for code re-use: in a language with polymorphism, programmers need only implement a data structure such as a list or an associative array once, rather than once for each type of element with which they plan to use it.
[src:cat-language/type-system] For this reason computer scientists sometimes call the use of certain forms of polymorphism *generic programming*.
[src:cat-language/type-system] The type-theoretic foundations of polymorphism are closely related to those of abstraction, modularity and (in some cases) subtyping.
[src:cat-language/type-system] Many type systems have been created that are specialized for use in certain environments with certain types of data, or for out-of-band static program analysis.
[src:cat-language/type-system] Frequently, these are based on ideas from formal type theory and are only available as part of prototype research systems.
[src:cat-language/type-system] The following table gives an overview over type theoretic concepts that are used in specialized type systems.
[src:cat-language/type-system] The names M, N, O range over terms and the names $\sigma ,\tau$ range over types.
[src:cat-language/type-system] Also referred to as *dependent sum type*, since ${\textstyle (x:\sigma )\times \tau =\sum _{x:\sigma }\tau }$ .
[src:cat-language/type-system] Dependent types are based on the idea of using scalars or values to more precisely describe the type of some other value.
[src:cat-language/type-system] For example, $\mathrm {matrix} (3,3)$ might be the type of a $3\times 3$ matrix.
[src:cat-language/type-system] where k, m, n are arbitrary positive integer values.
[src:cat-language/type-system] A variant of ML called Dependent ML has been created based on this type system, but because type checking for conventional dependent types is undecidable, not all programs using them can be type-checked without some kind of limits.
[src:cat-language/type-system] Dependent ML limits the sort of equality it can decide to Presburger arithmetic.
[src:cat-language/type-system] Other languages such as Epigram make the value of all expressions in the language decidable so that type checking can be decidable.
[src:cat-language/type-system] However, in general proof of decidability is undecidable, so many programs require hand-written annotations that may be very non-trivial.
[src:cat-language/type-system] As this impedes the development process, many language implementations provide an easy way out in the form of an option to disable this condition.
[src:cat-language/type-system] This, however, comes at the cost of making the type-checker run in an infinite loop when fed programs that do not type-check, causing the compilation to fail.
[src:cat-language/type-system] Linear types, based on the theory of linear logic, and closely related to uniqueness types, are types assigned to values having the property that they have one and only one reference to them at all times.
[src:cat-language/type-system] These are valuable for describing large immutable values such as files, strings, and so on, because any operation that simultaneously destroys a linear object and creates a similar object (such as `str = str + "a"`) can be optimized "under the hood" into an in-place mutation.
[src:cat-language/type-system] Normally this is not possible, as such mutations could cause side effects on parts of the program holding other references to the object, violating referential transparency.
[src:cat-language/type-system] They are also used in the prototype operating system Singularity for interprocess communication, statically ensuring that processes cannot share objects in shared memory to prevent race conditions.
[src:cat-language/type-system] The Clean language (a Haskell-like language) uses this type system to gain a lot of speed (compared to performing a deep copy) while remaining safe.
[src:cat-language/type-system] Intersection types are types describing values that belong to *both* of two other given types with overlapping value sets.
[src:cat-language/type-system] For example, in most implementations of C the signed char has range -128 to 127 and the unsigned char has range 0 to 255, so the intersection type of these two types would have range 0 to 127.
[src:cat-language/type-system] Such an intersection type could be safely passed into functions expecting *either* signed or unsigned chars, because it is compatible with both types.
[src:cat-language/type-system] Such a function could be passed into another function expecting an "`int` → `int`" function safely; it simply would not use the "`float` → `float`" functionality.
[src:cat-language/type-system] In a subclassing hierarchy, the intersection of a type and an ancestor type (such as its parent) is the most derived type.
[src:cat-language/type-system] The intersection of sibling types is empty.
[src:cat-language/type-system] The Forsythe language includes a general implementation of intersection types.
[src:cat-language/type-system] Union types are types describing values that belong to *either* of two types.
[src:cat-language/type-system] For example, in C, the signed char has a -128 to 127 range, and the unsigned char has a 0 to 255 range, so the union of these two types would have an overall "virtual" range of -128 to 255 that may be used partially depending on which union member is accessed.
[src:cat-language/type-system] Any function handling this union type would have to deal with integers in this complete range.
[src:cat-language/type-system] More generally, the only valid operations on a union type are operations that are valid on *both* types being unioned.
[src:cat-language/type-system] C's "union" concept is similar to union types, but is not typesafe, as it permits operations that are valid on *either* type, rather than *both*.
[src:cat-language/type-system] Union types are important in program analysis, where they are used to represent symbolic values whose exact nature (e.g., value or type) is not known.
[src:cat-language/type-system] In a subclassing hierarchy, the union of a type and an ancestor type (such as its parent) is the ancestor type.
[src:cat-language/type-system] The union of sibling types is a subtype of their common ancestor (that is, all operations permitted on their common ancestor are permitted on the union type, but they may also have other valid operations in common).
[src:cat-language/type-system] Existential types are frequently used in connection with record types to represent modules and abstract data types, due to their ability to separate implementation from interface.
[src:cat-language/type-system] For example, the type "T = ∃X { a: X; f: (X → int); }" describes a module interface that has a data member named *a* of type *X* and a function named *f* that takes a parameter of the *same* type *X* and returns an integer.
[src:cat-language/type-system] These types are both subtypes of the more general existential type T and correspond to concrete implementation types, so any value of one of these types is a value of type T.
[src:cat-language/type-system] Given a value "t" of type "T", we know that "t.f(t.a)" is well-typed, regardless of what the abstract type *X* is.
[src:cat-language/type-system] This gives flexibility for choosing types suited to a particular implementation, while clients that use only values of the interface type—the existential type—are isolated from these choices.
[src:cat-language/type-system] In general it's impossible for the typechecker to infer which existential type a given module belongs to.
[src:cat-language/type-system] In the above example intT { a: int; f: (int → int); } could also have the type ∃X { a: X; f: (X → int); }.
[src:cat-language/type-system] Although abstract data types and modules had been implemented in programming languages for quite some time, it wasn't until 1988 that John C.
[src:cat-language/type-system] Mitchell and Gordon Plotkin established the formal theory under the slogan: "Abstract [data] types have existential type".
[src:cat-language/type-system] The theory is a second-order typed lambda calculus similar to System F, but with existential instead of universal quantification.
[src:cat-language/type-system] In a type system with Gradual typing, variables may be assigned a type either at compile-time (which is static typing), or at runtime (which is dynamic typing).
[src:cat-language/type-system] This allows software developers to choose either type paradigm as appropriate, from within a single language.
[src:cat-language/type-system] Gradual typing uses a special type named *dynamic* to represent statically unknown types; gradual typing replaces the notion of type equality with a new relation called *consistency* that relates the dynamic type to every other type.
[src:cat-language/type-system] The consistency relation is symmetric but not transitive.
[src:cat-language/type-system] Many static type systems, such as those of C and Java, require *type declarations*: the programmer must explicitly associate each variable with a specific type.
[src:cat-language/type-system] Others, such as Haskell's, perform *type inference*: the compiler draws conclusions about the types of variables based on how programmers use those variables.
[src:cat-language/type-system] For example, given a function `f(x, y)` that adds `x` and `y` together, the compiler can infer that `x` and `y` must be numbers—since addition is only defined for numbers.
[src:cat-language/type-system] Thus, any call to `f` elsewhere in the program that specifies a non-numeric type (such as a string or list) as an argument would signal an error.
[src:cat-language/type-system] Numerical and string constants and expressions in code can and often do imply type in a particular context.
[src:cat-language/type-system] For example, an expression `3.14` might imply a type of floating-point, while `[1, 2, 3]` might imply a list of integers—typically an array.
[src:cat-language/type-system] Type inference is in general possible, if it is computable in the type system in question.
[src:cat-language/type-system] Moreover, even if inference is not computable in general for a given type system, inference is often possible for a large subset of real-world programs.
[src:cat-language/type-system] Haskell's type system, a version of Hindley–Milner, is a restriction of System Fω to so-called rank-1 polymorphic types, in which type inference is computable.
[src:cat-language/type-system] Most Haskell compilers allow arbitrary-rank polymorphism as an extension, but this makes type inference not computable.
[src:cat-language/type-system] A type system that assigns types to terms in type environments using typing rules is naturally associated with the decision problems of type checking, typability, and type inhabitation.
[src:cat-language/type-system] Some languages like C# or Scala have a unified type system.
[src:cat-language/type-system] This means that all C# types including primitive types inherit from a single root object.
[src:cat-language/type-system] Every type in C# inherits from the Object class.
[src:cat-language/type-system] Some languages, like Java and Raku, have a root type but also have primitive types that are not objects.
[src:cat-language/type-system] Java provides wrapper object types that exist together with the primitive types so developers can use either the wrapper object types or the simpler non-object primitive types.
[src:cat-language/type-system] Raku automatically converts primitive types to objects when their methods are accessed.
[src:cat-language/type-system] A type checker for a statically typed language must verify that the type of any expression is consistent with the type expected by the context in which that expression appears.
[src:cat-language/type-system] For example, in an assignment statement of the form `x := *e*`, the inferred type of the expression *`e`* must be consistent with the declared or inferred type of the variable `x`.
[src:cat-language/type-system] This notion of consistency, called *compatibility*, is specific to each programming language.
[src:cat-language/type-system] If the type of *`e`* and the type of `x` are the same, and assignment is allowed for that type, then this is a valid expression.
[src:cat-language/type-system] Thus, in the simplest type systems, the question of whether two types are compatible reduces to that of whether they are *equal* (or *equivalent*).
[src:cat-language/type-system] Different languages, however, have different criteria for when two type expressions are understood to denote the same type.
[src:cat-language/type-system] In languages with subtyping, the compatibility relation is more complex: If `B` is a subtype of `A`, then a value of type `B` can be used in a context where one of type `A` is expected (covariant), even if the reverse is not true.
[src:cat-language/type-system] Like equivalence, the subtype relation is defined differently for each programming language, with many variations possible.
[src:cat-language/type-system] The presence of parametric or ad hoc polymorphism in a language may also have implications for type compatibility.
